In article <1jemknINN1rv@gap.caltech.edu> hal@cco.caltech.edu (Hal Finney) writes:
>How about this for a statement of the problem:
>
>Communicants are A and B, spoofer is C.  All messages between A and B
>pass through C, who can change them.  A wishes to send a one bit message M
>to B without C discovering M.
>
>	A <-----> C <-----> B

OK.

Try this alternative:

	A <-----> B <-----> C

There is no spoofer.  A wishes to send a message to B without C discovering
it.  A and B have a secure channel.  B and C have a secure channel.  B
chooses to pass A's message along to C, without telling A.  How can A be
sure that B gets the message and C doesn't?

